{{nowrap|The Apple "A" series}} is a family of [[system on a chip|SoCs]] used in certain models of the [[iPhone]], [[iPad]], [[iPod Touch|iPod touch]], and the [[Apple TV]] digital media player. They integrate one or more [[ARM architecture|ARM-based]] processing cores ([[CPU]]), a graphics processing unit ([[GPU]]), [[CPU cache|cache memory]] and other electronics necessary to provide mobile computing functions within a single physical package. They are manufactured by [[Samsung]] and [[TSMC]].

=== Apple A4 ===
{{Main|Apple A4}}
The '''Apple A4''' is a PoP SoC manufactured by [[Samsung]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Clark |first=Don |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303912104575164112770784290?mod=rss_Today's_Most_Popular |title=Apple iPad Taps Familiar Component Suppliers - WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date=April 5, 2010 |accessdate=April 15, 2010}}</ref> It combines an [[ARM architecture|ARM]] [[ARM Cortex-A8|Cortex-A8]] CPU with a [[PowerVR]] GPU, and emphasizes power efficiency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/ipad/design/#performance |title=iPad - It's thin, light, powerful, and revolutionary |publisher=Apple |accessdate=July 7, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100706061702/http://www.apple.com/ipad/design/| archivedate= July 6, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>  The chip commercially debuted with the release of Apple's iPad [[tablet computer|tablet]];<ref name="Apple PR">{{cite press release|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2010/01/27Apple-Launches-iPad/ |title=Apple Launches iPad |publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |date=January 27, 2010 |accessdate=January 28, 2010}}</ref> followed shortly by the [[iPhone 4]] smartphone,<ref name="iPhoneA4">{{cite web |url=https://www.apple.com/iphone/design/index.html |title=iPhone 4 design |publisher=Apple |date=July 6, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706072512/https://www.apple.com/iphone/design/index.html |archive-date=July 6, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the 4th generation [[iPod Touch|iPod touch]] and the 2nd generation [[Apple TV]]. It was superseded in the [[iPad 2]], released the following year, by the [[Apple A5]] processor.

Apple A4 is based on the ARM processor architecture.<ref name="based_on_arm">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/22/technology/22chip.html |title=For Chip Makers, the Next Battle Is in Smartphones |newspaper=New York Times |date=February 21, 2010 |accessdate=February 25, 2010 |first=Ashlee |last=Vance| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100225065617/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/22/technology/22chip.html| archivedate= February 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> The first version released ran at 1&nbsp;GHz for the iPad<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.apple.com/kb/sp580 |title=iPad — Technical specifications |publisher=Apple |accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref> and contains an ARM Cortex-A8 CPU core paired with a [[PowerVR#Series5 (SGX)|PowerVR SGX 535]] [[graphics processing unit|graphics processor]] (GPU)<ref name="Apple PR" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/Apple-A4-Teardown/2204/3 |title=conclusion from both hard and software analysis it uses an ARM Cortex-A8 core |publisher=Ifixit.com |first=Kyle |last=Wiens |date=April 5, 2010 |accessdate=April 15, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100418145031/http://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/Apple-A4-Teardown/2204/3| archivedate= April 18, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name="Engadget">{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/02/23/ipad-confirmed-to-use-powervr-sgx-graphics/ |title=iPad confirmed to use PowerVR SGX graphics |date=February 23, 2010 |first=Donald |last=Melanson |publisher=Engadget}}</ref> built on Samsung's 45-nanometer (nm) silicon chip fabrication process.<ref name="EETimes-A4">{{cite web|first=Young |last=Choi |url=http://www.electronics-eetimes.com/en/analysis-gives-first-look-inside-apple-s-a4-processor.html?cmp_id=7&news_id=222901800 |title=Analysis gives first look inside Apple's A4 processor |publisher=[[EETimes]] |date=May 10, 2010 |accessdate=September 15, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915010243/http://www.electronics-eetimes.com/en/analysis-gives-first-look-inside-apple-s-a4-processor.html?cmp_id=7&news_id=222901800 |archivedate=September 15, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="Chipworks-A4">{{cite web |url=http://www.chipworks.com/A4_is_Samsung_45nm.aspx |title=Chipworks Confirms Apple A4 iPad chip is fabbed by Samsung in their 45-nm process |publisher=Chipworks |date=April 15, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921083904/http://chipworks.com/A4_is_Samsung_45nm.aspx |archivedate=September 21, 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The clock speed for the units used in the iPhone 4 and the iPod touch (4th generation) is 800&nbsp;[[MHz]]. The clock speed for the unit used in the Apple TV has not been revealed.

The Cortex-A8 core used in the A4 is thought to use performance enhancements developed by chip designer [[Intrinsity]], which was subsequently acquired by Apple,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/apple/news/2010/04/apple-purchase-of-intrinsity-confirmed.ars |title=Apple purchase of Intrinsity confirmed |publisher=Ars Technica |date=April 28, 2010 |first=Jon |last=Stokes |accessdate=April 28, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100428102017/http://arstechnica.com/apple/news/2010/04/apple-purchase-of-intrinsity-confirmed.ars| archivedate= April 28, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> in collaboration with Samsung.<ref name="Intrinsity">{{cite web |url=http://www.eetimes.com/news/latest/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=218600577 |publisher=EETimes.com |accessdate=April 23, 2010 |title=Samsung, Intrinsity pump ARM to&nbsp;GHz rate |first=Rick |last=Merritt}}</ref> The resulting core, dubbed "[[Samsung Hummingbird|Hummingbird]]", is able to run at far higher clock rates than other implementations while remaining fully compatible with the Cortex-A8 design provided by ARM.<ref name = "speed">{{cite web |url= http://www.pcworld.com/article/193597/Apple_iPad_Smokes_Past_the_iPhone_3GS_in_Speed_Test.html |title=Apple iPad smokes past the iPhone 3GS in speed |publisher=[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]] |date=April 6, 2010 |accessdate=April 11, 2010 |first=Gregg |last=Keizer| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100420062954/http://www.pcworld.com/article/193597/Apple_iPad_Smokes_Past_the_iPhone_3GS_in_Speed_Test.html| archivedate= April 20, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Other performance improvements include additional L2 cache. The same Cortex-A8 CPU core used in the A4 is also used in Samsung's S5PC110A01 SoC.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.eetimes.com/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=225700447 |title=Apple's A4 dissected, discussed...and tantalizing |publisher=EETimes.com |date=June 16, 2010 |first1=Paul |last1=Boldt |first2=Don |last2=Scansen | first3=Tim |last3=Whibley |accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ubmtechinsights.com/uploadedFiles/Apple%20A4%20vs%20SEC%20S5PC110A01.pdf |title=Microsoft PowerPoint - Apple A4 vs SEC S5PC110A01 |format=PDF |accessdate=July 7, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704204344/http://www.ubmtechinsights.com/uploadedFiles/Apple%20A4%20vs%20SEC%20S5PC110A01.pdf |archivedate=July 4, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The SGX535 in the A4 could theoretically push 35 million polygons per second and 500 million pixels per second, although real world performance may be considerably less.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.anandtech.com/show/4216/apple-ipad-2-gpu-performance-explored-powervr-sgx543mp2-benchmarked |title=Apple iPad 2 GPU Performance Explored: PowerVR SGX543MP2 Benchmarked - AnandTech :: Your Source for Hardware Analysis and News |publisher=[[AnandTech]] |accessdate=March 15, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110318205852/http://www.anandtech.com/show/4216/apple-ipad-2-gpu-performance-explored-powervr-sgx543mp2-benchmarked| archivedate= March 18, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>

The A4 processor package does not contain [[RAM]], but supports [[Package on package|PoP]] installation. Hence, there is a package with two low-power 128&nbsp;MB [[DDR SDRAM]] [[Integrated circuit|chips]] (totaling 256&nbsp;MB) mounted on top of the A4 used in the first-generation iPad, the [[IPod Touch 4th Generation|fourth-generation iPod touch]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/10/09/08/teardown_of_apples_4th_gen_ipod_touch_finds_256mb_of_ram.html |title=Teardown of Apple's 4th-gen iPod touch finds 256MB of RAM |publisher=Appleinsider.com |date=September 8, 2010 |accessdate=September 10, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100911215136/http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/10/09/08/teardown_of_apples_4th_gen_ipod_touch_finds_256mb_of_ram.html| archivedate= September 11, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> and the second-generation Apple TV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/Apple-TV-2nd-Generation-Teardown/3625/2 |title=Apple TV 2nd Generation Teardown |publisher=iFixit |date=September 30, 2010 |accessdate=January 4, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110102052816/http://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/Apple-TV-2nd-Generation-Teardown/3625/2| archivedate= January 2, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> The iPhone 4 has two 256&nbsp;MB packages for a total of 512&nbsp;MB.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/10/06/17/apple_reveals_iphone_4_has_512mb_ram_doubling_ipad_report.html |title=Apple reveals iPhone 4 has 512MB RAM, doubling iPad - report |work=[[AppleInsider]] |date=June 17, 2010 |accessdate=July 7, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100704124612/http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/10/06/17/apple_reveals_iphone_4_has_512mb_ram_doubling_ipad_report.html| archivedate= July 4, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ifixit.com/blog/2010/04/a-peek-inside-apples-a4-processor/ |title=A Peek Inside Apple’s A4 Processor |publisher=[[iFixit]] |date=April 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://community.cadence.com/cadence_blogs_8/b/ip/posts/apple-ipad_3a00_-no-lpddr2_3f00_ |title=Apple iPad: no LPDDR2? |publisher=Denali |date=April 9, 2010 |first=Marc |last=Greenberg}}</ref> The RAM is connected to the processor using ARM's [[64-bit computing|64-bit]]-wide [[ABMA 3 AXI|AMBA 3 AXI]] bus. To support the iPad's demand for high graphics bandwidth, the width of the RAM data bus is double that used in previous ARM11 and ARM9 based Apple devices.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eetasia.com/ART_8800603321_499495_NP_1e1373d9.HTM |title=iPad equipped to deliver richer graphics |work=[[EE Times Asia]] |date=April 9, 2010 |accessdate=April 14, 2010 |first=Rick |last=Merritt |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110927104038/http://www.eetasia.com/ART_8800603321_499495_NP_1e1373d9.HTM |archivedate=September 27, 2011 }}</ref>

=== Apple A5 ===
{{Main|Apple A5}}
The '''Apple A5''' is an SoC manufactured by [[Samsung]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4213981/Samsung-fabs-Apple-A5-processor |title= Updated: Samsung fabs Apple A5 processor | date= March 12, 2011 | publisher= EETimes.com| accessdate=March 15, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509081929/http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4213981/Samsung-fabs-Apple-A5-processor |archivedate=May 9, 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> that replaced the [[Apple A4|A4]]. The chip commercially debuted with the release of Apple's [[iPad 2]] [[tablet computer|tablet]] in March 2011,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://appleinsider.com/articles/11/03/02/apple_announces_ipad_2_with_new_design_faster_a5_processor|title=Apple announces redesigned iPad 2: A5 CPU, 2 cameras, ships March 11|website=AppleInsider}}</ref> followed by its release in the [[iPhone 4S]] [[smartphone]] later that year. Apple claims that compared with its predecessor, the A4, the A5 [[CPU]] "can do twice the work" and the [[Graphics processing unit|GPU]] has "up to nine times the graphics performance".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/ipad/features/ |title=Apple iPad 2 feature page |publisher=Apple.com |accessdate=March 15, 2011| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316162215/http://www.apple.com/ipad/features/ |archivedate=March 16, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

The A5 contains a dual-core [[ARM Cortex-A9 MPCore|ARM Cortex-A9]] CPU<ref name="anandtech1">{{cite web|url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/4215/apple-ipad-2-benchmarked-dualcore-cortex-a9-powervr-sgx-543mp2/2 |title=Apple iPad 2 Preview - AnandTech :: Your Source for Hardware Analysis and News |publisher=AnandTech |date= |accessdate=March 15, 2011}}</ref> with ARM's advanced [[SIMD]] extension, marketed as [[ARM NEON|NEON]], and a dual core [[PowerVR|PowerVR SGX543MP2]] GPU. This GPU can push between 70 and 80 million polygons/second and has a pixel fill rate of 2 billion pixels/second. Apple lists the A5 to be clocked at 1&nbsp;GHz on the iPad 2's technical specifications page,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.apple.com/kb/sp622 |title=iPad 2 - Technical Specifications |publisher=Apple |date= |accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref> though it can dynamically adjust its frequency to save battery life.<ref name="anandtech1"/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/11/03/13/inside_apples_ipad_2_a5_fast_lpddr2_ram_costs_66_more_than_tegra_2.html |title=Inside Apple's iPad 2 A5: fast LPDDR2 RAM, costs 66% more than Tegra 2 |publisher=[[AppleInsider]] |date= |accessdate=March 15, 2011}}</ref> The clock speed of the unit used in the iPhone 4S is 800&nbsp;MHz. Like the A4, the A5 process size is 45&nbsp;nm.<ref name="Chipworks-A5">{{cite web |url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/a-first-look-at-apples-a5-processor/ |title=A First Look at Apple's A5 Processor |publisher=Chipworks |date=March 12, 2011 |accessdate=September 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101053030/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/a-first-look-at-apples-a5-processor/ |archive-date=November 1, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

An updated [[32 nm]] version of the A5 processor was used in the third generation Apple TV, the [[iPod Touch (5th generation)|iPod touch (5th generation)]], the iPad Mini, and the new version of iPad 2 (version iPad2,4).<ref name="Chipworks-A5R2">{{cite web |url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/apple-a5-from-the-apple-tv-3-surprise-surprise/ |title=Update – 32-nm Apple A5 in the Apple TV 3 – and an iPad 2! |publisher=Chipworks |date=April 11, 2012 |accessdate=September 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024092806/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/apple-a5-from-the-apple-tv-3-surprise-surprise/ |archive-date=October 24, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The chip in the Apple TV has one core locked.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/12/03/18/single_core_a5_cpu_in_new_1080p_apple_tv_doubles_ram_to_512mb.html|title=Single-core A5 CPU in new 1080p Apple TV doubles RAM to 512MB|website=[[AppleInsider]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Update – 32-nm Apple A5 in the Apple TV 3 – and an iPad 2! |url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/technology-blog/2012/04/apple-a5-from-the-apple-tv-3-surprise-surprise/ |accessdate=April 12, 2012 |date=April 11, 2012 |publisher=ChipWorks |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413061858/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/technology-blog/2012/04/apple-a5-from-the-apple-tv-3-surprise-surprise/ |archive-date=April 13, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The markings of the square package indicates that it is named ''APL2498'', and in software, the chip is called ''S5L8942''. The [[32 nanometer|32&nbsp;nm]] variant of the A5 provides around 15% better battery life during web browsing, 30% better when playing 3D games and about 20% better battery life during video playback.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.anandtech.com/show/5789/the-ipad-24-review-32nm-a5-tested/2 |title=The iPad 2,4 Review: 32nm Brings Better Battery Life |publisher=[[AnandTech]] |date= |accessdate=November 1, 2012}}</ref>

In March 2013, Apple released an updated version of the third generation Apple TV (AppleTV3,2) containing a smaller, single-core version of the A5 processor.  Unlike the other A5 variants, this version of the A5 is not a PoP, having no stacked RAM. The chip is very small, just 6.1×6.2&nbsp;mm, but as the decrease in size is not due to a decrease in feature size (it is still on a 32&nbsp;nm fabrication process), this indicates that this A5 revision is of a new design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.macrumors.com/2013/03/12/a5-chip-in-tweaked-apple-tv-still-manufactured-by-samsung/|title=A5 Chip in Tweaked Apple TV Still Manufactured by Samsung at 32nm|publisher=}}</ref> Markings tell that it is named ''APL7498'', and in software, the chip is called ''S5L8947''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.macrumors.com/2013/03/10/tweaked-apple-tv-contains-die-shrunk-a5-chip-not-a5x/|title=Tweaked Apple TV Contains Die-Shrunk A5 Chip, Not A5X|publisher=}}</ref><ref name="Chipworks-A5-singlecore">{{cite web |url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-latest-apple-a5-from-a-new-apple-tv/ |title=Apple’s TV surprise – a new A5 chip! |publisher=Chipworks |date=March 12, 2013 |accessdate=September 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110141408/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-latest-apple-a5-from-a-new-apple-tv/ |archive-date=November 10, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

=== Apple A5X ===
{{Main|Apple A5X}}
The '''Apple A5X''' is an SoC announced on March 7, 2012, at the launch of the [[iPad (3rd generation)|third-generation iPad]]. It is a high-performance variant of the [[Apple A5]]; Apple claims it has twice the graphics performance of the A5.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2012/03/07Apple-Launches-New-iPad.html |title=Apple Launches New iPad |publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |date=March 7, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> It was superseded in the [[iPad (4th generation)|fourth-generation iPad]] by the [[Apple A6X]] processor.

The A5X has a quad-core graphics unit (PowerVR SGX543MP4) instead of the previous dual-core as well as a quad-channel memory controller that provides a memory bandwidth of 12.8&nbsp;GB/s, roughly three times more than in the A5. The added graphics cores and extra memory channels add up to a very large die size of 165&nbsp;mm²,<ref name="Chipworks-A5X">{{cite web |url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/the-apple-a5x-versus-the-a5-and-a4-big-is-beautiful |title=The Apple A5X versus the A5 and A4 – Big Is Beautiful |publisher=Chipworks |date=March 19, 2012 |accessdate=September 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205095719/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/the-apple-a5x-versus-the-a5-and-a4-big-is-beautiful |archive-date=December 5, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> for example twice the size of [[Nvidia]] [[Tegra 3]].<ref name="anandtech.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/5685/apple-a5x-die-size-measured-16294mm2-likely-still-45nm |title=Apple A5X Die Size Measured: 162.94mm^2, Samsung 45nm LP Confirmed |publisher=AnandTech |date= |accessdate=November 1, 2012}}</ref> This is mainly due to the large PowerVR SGX543MP4 GPU. The clock frequency of the dual ARM Cortex-A9 cores have been shown to operate at the same 1&nbsp;GHz frequency as in A5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/5670/the-frequency-of-apple-a5x-in-the-new-ipad-confirmed-still-running-at-1ghz |title=The Frequency of Apple A5X in the New iPad Confirmed: Still Running at 1GHz |publisher=AnandTech |date= |accessdate=November 1, 2012}}</ref> The RAM in A5X is separate from the main CPU package.<ref>{{cite web|title=iFixit teardown of the 3rd generation iPad.|url=http://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPad-3-4G-Teardown/8277/2|publisher=iFixit}}</ref>
{{clear}}

=== Apple A6 ===
{{Main|Apple A6}}
The '''Apple A6''' is a PoP SoC introduced on September 12, 2012, at the launch of the [[iPhone 5]], then a year later was inherited by its minor successor the [[iPhone 5C]]. Apple states that it is up to twice as fast and has up to twice the graphics power compared to its predecessor the [[Apple A5]].<ref name="Apple iPhone 5 PR">{{citation |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2012/09/12Apple-Introduces-iPhone-5.html |title=Apple Introduces iPhone 5 |publisher=Apple.com |date=September 12, 2012 |accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref> It is 22% smaller and draws less power than the 45&nbsp;nm A5.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/09/12/iphone-5-processor/|title=Apple: A6 chip in iPhone 5 has 2x CPU power, 2x graphics performance, yet consumes less energy|publisher=}}</ref>

The A6 is said to use a 1.3&nbsp;GHz<ref name="Engadget-A6-1.3GHz">{{citation |url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/09/26/apple-a6-cpu-13ghz-geekbench-confirmed-overclocking// |title=Apple's A6 CPU actually clocked at around 1.3 GHz, per new Geekbench report |publisher=Engadget |date=September 26, 2012 |accessdate=September 26, 2012}}</ref> custom<ref name="NotanA15" /> Apple-designed [[ARM architecture|ARMv7]] based [[Multi-core processor|dual-core CPU]], called Swift,<ref name="A6NamedSwift">{{cite web |first1=Anand |last1=Lal Shimpi |first2=Brian |last2=Klug |first3=Vivek |last3=Gowri  |url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/6330/the-iphone-5-review/5 |title=The iPhone 5 Review - Decoding Swift |publisher=AnandTech |date=October 16, 2012 |accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref> rather than a licensed CPU from ARM like in previous designs, and an integrated 266&nbsp;MHz triple-core [[PowerVR]] SGX 543MP3<ref name="AnandTechDieShot">{{cite web |url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/6323/apple-a6-die-revealed-3core-gpu-100mm2 |title=Apple A6 Die Revealed: 3-core GPU, <100mm^2 |publisher=AnandTech |date=September 21, 2012 |accessdate=September 22, 2012}}</ref> [[graphics processing unit]] (GPU).  The Swift core in the A6 uses a new tweaked instruction set, ARMv7s, featuring some elements of the [[ARM Cortex-A15 MPCore|ARM Cortex-A15]] such as support for the [[ARM architecture|Advanced SIMD v2]], and [[VFP (instruction set)|VFPv4]].<ref name="NotanA15"/> The A6 is manufactured by Samsung on a [[High-k dielectric|high-κ]] [[metal gate]] (HKMG) 32&nbsp;nm process.<ref name="Chipworks-A6">{{cite web|url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/apple-iphone-5-the-a6-application-processor/ |title=Apple iPhone 5 – the A6 Application Processor |publisher=Chipworks |date=September 21, 2012 |accessdate=September 15, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922151159/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/apple-iphone-5-the-a6-application-processor/ |archivedate=September 22, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>

=== Apple A6X ===
{{Main|Apple A6X}}
'''Apple A6X''' is an SoC introduced at the launch of the [[iPad (4th generation)|fourth-generation iPad]] on October 23, 2012.  It is a high-performance variant of the [[Apple A6]]. Apple claims the A6X has twice the CPU performance and up to twice the graphics performance of its predecessor, the [[Apple A5X]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2012/10/23Apple-Introduces-iPad-mini.html |title=Apple Introduces iPad mini |publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |date=October 23, 2012 |accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref>

Like the A6, this SoC continues to use the dual-core Swift CPU, but it has a new quad core GPU, quad channel memory and slightly higher 1.4&nbsp;GHz CPU clock rate.<ref name="AnandTech-iPad4GPU">{{cite web |first=Anand |last=Lal Shimpi |url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/6426/ipad-4-gpu-performance-analyzed-powervr-sgx-554mp4-under-the-hood |title=iPad 4 GPU Performance Analyzed: PowerVR SGX 554MP4 Under the Hood  |publisher=AnandTech |date=November 2, 2012 |accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref> It uses an integrated quad-core [[PowerVR]] SGX 554MP4 [[graphics processing unit]] (GPU) running at 300&nbsp;MHz and a quad-channel [[Memory controller|memory subsystem]].<ref name="AnandTech-iPad4GPU" /><ref name="Chipworks-A6X">{{cite web |url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-apple-ipad-4-a6x-a-very-new-beast/ |title=Inside the Apple iPad 4 – A6X a very new beast! |publisher=Chipworks |date=November 1, 2012 |accessdate=September 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518010605/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-apple-ipad-4-a6x-a-very-new-beast/ |archive-date=May 18, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Compared to the A6 the A6X is 30% larger, but it continues to be manufactured by Samsung on a [[High-k dielectric|high-κ]] [[metal gate]] (HKMG) 32&nbsp;nm process.<ref name="Chipworks-A6X" />

=== Apple A7 ===
{{Main|Apple A7}}
The '''Apple A7''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] PoP SoC whose first appearance was in the [[iPhone 5S]], which was introduced on September 10, 2013. The chip would also be used in the [[iPad Air]], [[iPad Mini 2]] and [[iPad Mini 3]]. Apple states that it is up to twice as fast and has up to twice the graphics power compared to its predecessor the Apple A6.<ref name="Apple iPhone 5s PR">{{cite web |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2013/09/10Apple-Announces-iPhone-5s-The-Most-Forward-Thinking-Smartphone-in-the-World.html |title=Apple Announces iPhone 5s—The Most Forward-Thinking Smartphone in the World |publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |date=September 10, 2013 |accessdate=September 13, 2013}}</ref>

The A7 features an Apple-designed 1.3<ref name="AnandTech-iPhone5s-A7">{{cite web |first=Anand |last=Lal Shimpi |url=http://anandtech.com/show/7335/the-iphone-5s-review/2 |title=The iPhone 5s Review: A7 SoC Explained |publisher=AnandTech |date= September 17, 2013 |accessdate= September 18, 2013}}</ref>–1.4<ref name="AnandTech-iPadAir-CPU">{{cite web |last=Lai Shimpi |first=Anand |url=http://anandtech.com/show/7460/apple-ipad-air-review/3 |title=The iPad Air Review: iPhone to iPad: CPU Changes |publisher=AnandTech |date=October 29, 2013 |accessdate=October 30, 2013}}</ref>&nbsp;GHz 64-bit<ref name="AnandTech-iPhone5s-64-bit">{{cite web |first=Anand |last=Lal Shimpi |url=http://anandtech.com/show/7335/the-iphone-5s-review/4 |title=The iPhone 5s Review: The Move to 64-bit |publisher=AnandTech |date= September 17, 2013 |accessdate= September 18, 2013}}</ref> [[ARMv8|ARMv8-A]]<ref name="AnandTech-iPhone5s-Cyclone">{{cite web |first=Anand |last=Lal Shimpi |url=http://anandtech.com/show/7335/the-iphone-5s-review/3 |title=The iPhone 5s Review: After Swift Comes Cyclone |publisher=AnandTech |date= September 17, 2013 |accessdate= September 18, 2013}}</ref><ref name="LLVM-5s-ARMv8-A">{{cite mailing list|url=http://lists.llvm.org/pipermail/llvm-dev/2013-September/065449.html |title=[LLVMdev&#93; A7 processor support? |first=Chris |last=Lattner |authorlink=Chris Lattner |mailing-list=llvm-dev |date=September 10, 2013 |accessdate=July 9, 2017}}</ref> dual-core CPU,<ref name="AnandTech-iPhone5s-A7" /> called Cyclone,<ref name="AnandTech-iPhone5s-Cyclone" /> and an integrated [[PowerVR#Series 6 (Rogue)|PowerVR G6430]] GPU in a four cluster configuration.<ref name="AnandTech-iPhone5s-GPU">{{cite web |first=Anand |last=Lal Shimpi |url=http://anandtech.com/show/7335/the-iphone-5s-review/7 |title=The iPhone 5s Review: GPU Architecture |date= September 17, 2013 |publisher=AnandTech |accessdate= September 18, 2013}}</ref> The ARMv8-A architecture doubles the number of [[Processor register|registers]] of the A7 compared to the A6.<ref name="Ars: Apple unveils">{{cite web |last=Cunningham |first=Andrew |url= https://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/09/apple-unveils-64-bit-iphone-5s/ |title=Apple unveils 64-bit iPhone 5S with fingerprint scanner, $199 for 16GB |publisher=Ars Technica |date=September 10, 2013 |accessdate=September 12, 2013}}</ref> It now has 31 general-purpose registers that are each [[64-bit computing|64-bits]] wide and 32 floating-point/[[ARM NEON|NEON]] registers that are each 128-bits wide.<ref name="AnandTech-iPhone5s-64-bit" /> The A7 is manufactured by Samsung on a [[High-k dielectric|high-κ]] [[metal gate]] (HKMG) [[28 nanometer|28 nm]] process<ref name="Chipworks-iPhone5s">{{cite web|url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-iphone-5s/|title=Inside the iPhone 5s|first1=Jason|last1=Tanner|first2=Jim|last2=Morrison|first3=Dick|last3=James|first4=Ray|last4=Fontaine|first5=Phil|last5=Gamache|publisher=Chipworks|date=September 20, 2013|accessdate=September 20, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803201521/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-iphone-5s/|archivedate=August 3, 2014}}</ref> and the chip includes over 1 billion [[Transistor count|transistors]] on a die 102&nbsp;mm<sup>2</sup> in size.<ref name="AnandTech-iPhone5s-A7" />

=== Apple A8 ===
{{Main|Apple A8}}
The '''Apple A8''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] PoP SoC manufactured by TSMC. Its first appearance was in the [[iPhone 6]] and [[iPhone 6 Plus]], which were introduced on September 9, 2014.<ref name="Apple iPhone 6 PR">{{cite press release |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2014/09/09Apple-Announces-iPhone-6-iPhone-6-Plus-The-Biggest-Advancements-in-iPhone-History.html |title=Apple Announces iPhone 6 & iPhone 6 Plus—The Biggest Advancements in iPhone History |publisher=Apple |date=September 9, 2014 |accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref> A year later it would drive the [[iPad Mini 4]]. Apple states that it has 25% more CPU performance and 50% more graphics performance while drawing only 50% of the power compared to its predecessor, the [[Apple A7]].<ref name="Verge A8">{{cite news |last=Savov |first=Vlad |title=iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus have a new faster A8 processor |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/9/9/6127111/iphone-6-and-iphone-6-plus-have-a-new-faster-a8-processor |work=The Verge |publisher=Vox Media |date=September 9, 2014 |accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref> On February 9, 2018 Apple released the HomePod, which is powered by an Apple A8 with 1 GB of RAM.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/HomePod++Teardown/103133|title=HomePod Teardown|date=2018-02-12|work=iFixit|access-date=2018-02-13|language=en}}</ref>

The A8 features an Apple-designed 1.4<ref name="A8’s CPU: What Comes After Cyclone?"/>&nbsp;GHz 64-bit<ref name="A8: Apple’s First 20nm SoC"/> [[ARMv8|ARMv8-A]]<ref name="A8: Apple’s First 20nm SoC"/> dual-core CPU, and an integrated custom [[PowerVR#Series 6XT|PowerVR GX6450]] GPU in a four cluster configuration.<ref name="A8’s CPU: What Comes After Cyclone?"/> The GPU features custom shader cores and compiler designed by Apple.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.realworldtech.com/apple-custom-gpu/|title=A Look Inside Apple’s Custom GPU for the iPhone|last=Kanter|first=David|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> The A8 is manufactured on a 20&nbsp;nm process<ref name="AnandTech-Apple-Announces-A8">{{cite web |last=Smith |first=Ryan |url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/8504/apple-announces-a8-soc |title=Apple Announces A8 SoC |publisher=AnandTech |date=September 9, 2014 |accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref> by [[TSMC]],<ref name="Chipworks-iPhone6">{{cite web|url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-iphone-6-and-iphone-6-plus/|title=Inside the iPhone 6 and iPhone 6 Plus|publisher=Chipworks|date=September 19, 2014|accessdate=September 20, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924015413/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-iphone-6-and-iphone-6-plus/|archive-date=September 24, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> which replaced [[Samsung]] as the manufacturer of Apple's mobile device processors. It contains 2 billion transistors. Despite that being double the number of transistors compared to the A7, its physical size has been reduced by 13% to 89&nbsp;mm<sup>2</sup> (consistent with a shrink only, not known to be a new microarchitecture).<ref name="extremetech">{{cite web|last1=Anthony|first1=Sebastian|title=Apple’s A8 SoC analyzed: The iPhone 6 chip is a 2-billion-transistor 20nm monster|url=http://www.extremetech.com/computing/189787-apples-a8-soc-analyzed-the-iphone-6-chip-is-a-2-billion-transistor-20nm-monster|website=www.extremetech.com|publisher=ExtremeTech|accessdate=September 10, 2014}}</ref>

=== Apple A8X ===
{{Main|Apple A8X}}
The '''Apple A8X''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] SoC introduced at the launch of the [[iPad Air 2]] on October 16, 2014.<ref name="Apple iPad Air 2 PR">{{cite press release |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2014/10/16Apple-Introduces-iPad-Air-2-The-Thinnest-Most-Powerful-iPad-Ever.html |title=Apple Introduces iPad Air 2—The Thinnest, Most Powerful iPad Ever |publisher=Apple |date=October 16, 2014 |accessdate=October 16, 2014}}</ref> It is a high performance variant of the [[Apple A8]]. Apple states that it has 40% more CPU performance and 2.5 times the graphics performance of its predecessor, the [[Apple A7]].<ref name="Apple iPad Air 2 PR" /><ref name="Apple Performance">{{cite web |url=https://www.apple.com/ipad-air-2/performance/ |title=iPad Air 2 - Performance |publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |date=October 16, 2014 |accessdate=October 16, 2014}}</ref>

Unlike the A8, this SoC uses a [[triple-core]] [[Central processing unit|CPU]], a new [[octa-core]] [[Graphics processing unit|GPU]], [[Dual channel memory architecture|dual channel memory]] and slightly higher 1.5&nbsp;GHz CPU clock rate.<ref name="Apple A8X's GPU"/> It uses an integrated custom octa-core [[PowerVR]] GXA6850 [[graphics processing unit]] (GPU) running at 450&nbsp;MHz and a dual-channel [[Memory controller|memory subsystem]].<ref name="Apple A8X's GPU"/> It is manufactured by [[TSMC]] on their 20&nbsp;nm fabrication process, and consists of 3 billion [[Transistor count|transistors]].

=== Apple A9 ===
{{Main|Apple A9}}
The '''Apple A9''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[ARMv8-A|ARM-based]] SoC that first appeared in the [[iPhone 6S]] and 6S Plus, which were introduced on September 9, 2015.<ref name="Apple iPhone 6S PR">{{cite press release |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2015/09/09Apple-Introduces-iPhone-6s-iPhone-6s-Plus.html |title=Apple Introduces iPhone 6s & iPhone 6s Plus |publisher=Apple |date=September 9, 2015 |accessdate=September 9, 2015}}</ref> Apple states that it has 70% more CPU performance and 90% more graphics performance compared to its predecessor, the [[Apple A8]].<ref name="Apple iPhone 6S PR" /> It is dual sourced, a first for an Apple SoC; it is manufactured by Samsung on their 14&nbsp;nm FinFET LPE process and by TSMC on their 16&nbsp;nm FinFET process. It was subsequently included in the [[iPhone SE (1st generation)|first-generation iPhone SE]], and the [[iPad (2017)]].

=== Apple A9X ===
{{Main|Apple A9X}}
The '''Apple A9X''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] SoC that was announced on September 9, 2015, and released on November 11, 2015, and first appeared in the [[iPad Pro]].<ref name="Apple iPad Pro PR">{{cite press release |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2015/09/09Apple-Introduces-iPad-Pro-Featuring-Epic-12-9-inch-Retina-Display.html |title=Apple Introduces iPad Pro Featuring Epic 12.9-inch Retina Display |publisher=Apple |date=September 9, 2015 |accessdate=September 9, 2015}}</ref> It offers 80% more CPU performance and two times the GPU performance of its predecessor, the [[Apple A8X]]. It is manufactured by [[TSMC]] using a [[16 nm]] [[FinFET]] process.<ref name="ArsTechnica iPad Pro">{{cite web|title=Apple’s new iPad Pro is an expansive 12.9 inches, available in November|url=https://arstechnica.com/apple/2015/09/apples-new-ipad-2-pro-is-an-expansive-12-9-inches/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref>

=== Apple A10 Fusion ===
{{Main|Apple A10}}
The '''Apple A10 Fusion''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[ARMv8-A|ARM-based]] SoC that first appeared in the [[iPhone 7]] and 7 Plus, which were introduced on September 7, 2016.<ref name="Apple iPhone 7 PR">{{cite press release |url=https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2016/09/07Apple-Introduces-iPhone-7-iPhone-7-Plus-The-Best-Most-Advanced-iPhone-Ever.html |title=Apple Introduces iPhone 7 & iPhone 7 Plus —The Best, Most Advanced iPhone Ever |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |date=September 7, 2016 |accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref> The A10 is also featured in the [[iPad (2018)|2018 iPad]], [[iPad (2019)|2019 iPad]] and [[iPod Touch (7th generation)|7th generation iPod Touch]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/ipod-touch/|title=iPod touch|website=Apple|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> It has a new quad core design with two high performance cores, and two smaller highly efficient cores. It is 40% faster than the A9, with 50% faster graphics. It is made by TSMC on their 16&nbsp;nm FinFET process.

=== Apple A10X Fusion ===
{{Main|Apple A10X}}
The '''Apple A10X Fusion''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[ARMv8-A|ARM-based]] SoC that first appeared in the 10.5" [[iPad Pro]] and the second generation of the 12.9" iPad Pro, which were both announced on June 5, 2017.<ref name="Apple iPad Pro 10.5 PR">{{cite press release |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2017/06/ipad-pro-10-5-and-12-9-inch-models-introduces-worlds-most-advanced-display-breakthrough-performance/ |title=iPad Pro, in 10.5-inch and 12.9-inch models, introduces the world’s most advanced display and breakthrough performance |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |date=June 5, 2017 |accessdate=June 5, 2017}}</ref> It is a variant of the [[Apple A10|A10]] and Apple claims that it has 30 percent faster CPU performance and 40 percent faster GPU performance than its predecessor, the [[Apple A9X|A9X]].<ref name="Apple iPad Pro 10.5 PR" /> On September 12, 2017, Apple announced that the [[Apple TV 4K]] would be powered by an A10X chip. It is made by TSMC on their 10&nbsp;nm FinFET process.<ref name="TechInsights-A10X">{{cite web |last=Wei |first=Andy |url=http://www.techinsights.com/about-techinsights/overview/blog/10nm-rollout-marching-right-along/ |title=10 nm Process Rollout Marching Right Along |publisher=TechInsights |date=June 29, 2017 |accessdate=June 30, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803141307/http://www.techinsights.com/about-techinsights/overview/blog/10nm-rollout-marching-right-along/ |archive-date=August 3, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

=== Apple A11 Bionic ===
{{Main|Apple A11}}
The '''Apple A11 Bionic''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[ARMv8-A|ARM-based]] SoC <ref name="Apple iPhone 8 PR">{{cite press release |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2017/09/iphone-8-and-iphone-8-plus-a-new-generation-of-iphone/ |title=iPhone 8 and iPhone 8 Plus: A new generation of iPhone |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate= September 12, 2017}}</ref> that first appeared in the [[iPhone 8]], iPhone 8 Plus, and [[iPhone X]] which were introduced on September 12, 2017.<ref name="Apple iPhone 8 PR" /> It has two high-performance cores which are 25% faster than the [[Apple A10|A10 Fusion]] and four high-efficiency cores which are 70% faster than the energy-efficient cores in the A10.<ref name="Apple iPhone 8 PR" /><ref name="iPhone 8 A11">{{cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-8/#a11 |title=iPhone 8:A11 Bionic |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |date=September 12, 2017 |access-date= September 12, 2017}}</ref>

=== Apple A12 Bionic ===
{{Main|Apple A12}}
The '''Apple A12 Bionic''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[ARM architecture|ARM-based]] SoC that first appeared in the [[iPhone XS]], [[iPhone XS|XS Max]] and [[iPhone XR|XR]] which were introduced on September 12, 2018. It is also within the 2019 models of the [[iPad Air]] and [[iPad Mini]]. It has two high-performance cores which are 15% faster than the A11 Bionic and four high-efficiency cores which are 50% lower power usage than the energy-efficient cores in the A11 Bionic.<ref name="Apple A12 Bionic">{{cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-xs/a12-bionic/ |title=A12 Bionic |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |date=September 12, 2018 |access-date= November 22, 2018}}</ref> The A12 is manufactured by [[TSMC]]<ref name="Engadget 7nm" /> using a [[7 nanometer|7&nbsp;nm]]<ref name="Apple iPhone XS PR">{{cite press release |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2018/09/iphone-xs-and-iphone-xs-max-bring-the-best-and-biggest-displays-to-iphone/ |title=iPhone Xs and iPhone Xs Max bring the best and biggest displays to iPhone |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate= September 12, 2018}}</ref> [[FinFET]] process, the first to ship in a smartphone.<ref name="AnandTech iPhone XS">{{cite web |last=Smith |first=Ryan |url=https://www.anandtech.com/show/13360/apple-announces-2018-iphones-iphone-xs-xr |title=Apple Announces the 2018 iPhones: iPhone XS, iPhone XS Max, & iPhone XR |work=[[AnandTech]] |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Engadget 7nm">{{cite web |last=Summers |first=Nick |url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/09/12/apple-a12-bionic-7-nanometer-chip/ |title=Apple's A12 Bionic is the first 7-nanometer smartphone chip |work=[[Engadget]] |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 12, 2018}}</ref>

=== Apple A12X Bionic ===
{{Main|Apple A12X}}
The '''Apple A12X Bionic''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[ARM architecture|ARM-based]] SoC that first appeared in the 11.0" [[iPad Pro]] and the third generation of the 12.9" iPad Pro, which were both announced on October 30, 2018.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2018/10/new-ipad-pro-with-all-screen-design-is-most-advanced-powerful-ipad-ever/|title=New iPad Pro with all-screen design Is most advanced, powerful iPad ever|date=October 30, 2018|publisher=Apple}}</ref> It offers 35% faster single-core and 90% faster multi-core CPU performance than its predecessor, the A10X. It has four high-performance cores and four high-efficiency cores. The A12X is manufactured by [[TSMC]] using a [[7 nanometer|7&nbsp;nm]] [[FinFET]] process, the first to ship in a tablet.

=== Apple A12Z Bionic ===
{{Main|Apple A12Z}}
The '''Apple A12Z Bionic''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[ARM architecture|ARM-based]] SoC based on the A12X that first appeared in the second 11.0" and the fourth generation of the 12.9" [[iPad Pro]] which were both announced on March 18, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/18/apple-unveils-new-ipad-pro-with-magic-keyboard-case-available-to-order-today/|title=Apple unveils new iPad Pro with backlit Magic Keyboard case, available to order today|last=Miller|first=Chance|date=2020-03-18|website=9to5Mac|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>

=== Apple A13 Bionic ===
{{Main|Apple A13 Bionic}}
The '''Apple A13 Bionic''' is a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[ARM architecture|ARM-based]] SoC that first appeared in the [[iPhone 11]], [[iPhone 11 Pro|11 Pro]], and [[iPhone 11 Pro Max|11 Pro Max]] which were introduced on September 10, 2019. It is also featured in the [[iPhone SE (2nd generation)|second-generation iPhone SE]] which was introduced on April 15, 2020.

== S series ==
The Apple "S" series is a family of [[System in package|Systems in Package (SiP)]] used in the [[Apple Watch]]. It uses a customized [[Central processing unit|application processor]] that together with [[Random-access memory|memory]], [[Flash memory|storage]] and support processors for wireless connectivity, sensors and [[I/O]] comprise a complete computer in a single package. They are designed by Apple, and manufactured by contract manufacturers such as [[Samsung]].

=== Apple S1 ===
{{Main|Apple S1}}
The '''Apple S1''' is an integrated computer designed by Apple. It includes memory, storage and support circuits like [[wireless modem]]s and I/O controllers in a sealed integrated package. It was announced on September 9, 2014 as part of the "Wish we could say more" event. Its first appearance was in the original [[Apple Watch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technobuffalo.com/2014/09/09/apple-watch-uses-a-new-s1-chip-heart-rate-monitor/|title=Apple Watch Uses a New S1 Chip & Heart Rate Monitor|first=Jacob |last=Kleinman|date=September 9, 2014}}</ref>

=== Apple S1P ===
Used in [[Apple Watch Series 1]]. It has a dual-core processor almost identical to the S2, with the exception of the built-in [[GPS receiver]].

=== Apple S2 ===
{{Main|Apple S2}}
Used in the [[Apple Watch Series 2]]. It has a dual-core processor and a built-in GPS receiver.

=== Apple S3 ===
{{Main|Apple S3}}
Used in the [[Apple Watch Series 3]]. It has a dual-core processor that is 70% faster than the Apple S2 and a built-in GPS receiver.<ref name="apple-watch-series-3-pr">{{cite press release|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2017/09/apple-watch-series-3-features-built-in-cellular-and-more/|title=Apple Watch Series 3 brings built-in cellular, powerful new health and fitness enhancements|date=September 12, 2017|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]}}</ref> There is also an option for a cellular modem and an internal [[eSIM]] module.<ref name="apple-watch-series-3-pr"/> It also includes the W2 chip.<ref name="apple-watch-series-3-pr"/>

=== Apple S4 ===
{{Main|Apple S4}}
Used in the [[Apple Watch Series 4]]. It has an Apple designed custom 64-bit dual-core processor with up to 2× faster performance. It also contains the W3 wireless chip, which supports [[Bluetooth 5]].

=== Apple S5 ===
Used in the [[Apple Watch Series 5]]. It has the same Apple designed custom 64-bit dual-core processor and GPU as the S4,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/stroughtonsmith/status/1174376928758968320|title=According to Xcode, Apple Watch Series 5 has the same generation CPU/GPU as the Apple Watch Series 4; I guess the only changes are a gyro and 32GB of NAND? The plus side of that is that we won't have to worry about watchOS being slower on the Series 4 than on a brand new model|last=Troughton-Smith|first=Steve|date=2019-09-18|website=@stroughtonsmith|language=en|access-date=2019-09-19}}</ref> with the exception of the built-in [[magnetometer]].

== T series ==
=== Apple T1 ===
The Apple T1 chip is an [[ARMv7]] SoC from Apple driving the [[System Management Controller]] (SMC) and [[Touch ID]] sensor of the [[MacBook Pro#Fourth generation|2016 and 2017 MacBook Pro with Touch Bar]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Ryan|title=Apple Announces 4th Generation MacBook Pro Family: Thinner, Lighter, with Thunderbolt 3 & "Touchbar"|url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/10799/apple-announces-4th-generation-macbook-pro-family-thinner-lighter-with-thunderbolt-3-touch-bar|accessdate=27 October 2016|publisher=[[Anandtech]]|date=27 October 2016}}</ref> This chip operates as a secure enclave for the processing and encryption of fingerprints as well as acting as a gatekeeper to the microphone and FaceTime HD camera protecting these possible targets from potential hacking attempts. The T1 runs bridgeOS,<ref name=arswatchosvariant /> a variant of [[watchOS]],<ref name=arswatchosvariant /> separate from the [[Intel]] CPU running [[macOS]].<ref name=arswatchosvariant>{{cite news|last1=Cunningham|first1=Andrew|title=15 hours with the 13" MacBook Pro, and how Apple’s T1 bridges ARM and Intel|url=https://arstechnica.com/apple/2016/10/15-hours-with-the-13-macbook-pro-and-how-apples-t1-bridges-arm-and-intel/|accessdate=4 December 2018|publisher=[[Ars Technica]]|date=28 October 2016}}</ref>

=== Apple T2 ===
The Apple T2 chip is a SoC from Apple first released in the [[iMac Pro|iMac Pro 2017]]. It is a 64-bit ARMv8 chip (a variant of the A10, or T8010), and runs a separate operating system called bridgeOS 2.0,<ref>{{cite web |last=Parrish |first=Kevin |title=Apple’s T2 chip may be causing issues in iMac Pro and 2018 MacBook Pros |url= https://www.digitaltrends.com/computing/apple-t2-chip-may-be-causing-imac-pro-macbook-problems/ |website=[[DigitalTrends]] |accessdate=22 January 2019 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180918223447/https://www.digitaltrends.com/computing/apple-t2-chip-may-be-causing-imac-pro-macbook-problems/ |archivedate=18 September 2018 |date=24 July 2018 |quote=Of all the error messages uploaded to these threads, there is one detail they seem to share: Bridge OS. This is an embedded operating system used by Apple’s stand-alone T2 security chip, which provides the iMac Pro with a secure boot, encrypted storage, live “Hey Siri” commands, and so on.}}</ref> which is a watchOS derivative.<ref>{{cite tweet |user= stroughtonsmith |number= 791790949131231233 |date= 27 October 2016 |title= And there you have it. Apple's T1 chip runs an iOS (technically watchOS for armv7k) variant |last= Troughton-Smith |first= Steven }}</ref> It provides a secure enclave for encrypted keys, gives users the ability to lock down the computer's boot process, handles system functions like the camera and audio control, and handles on-the-fly encryption and decryption for the [[solid-state drive]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.macrumors.com/2017/12/14/imac-pro-has-t2-chip-with-secure-boot/|title=iMac Pro Features Apple's Custom T2 Chip With Secure Boot Capabilities|website=[[MacRumors]]|date=14 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.computerworld.com/article/3290415/apple-mac/the-macbook-pro-s-t2-chip-boosts-enterprise-security.html|title=The MacBook Pro’s T2 chip boosts enterprise security|first=Jonny|last=Evans|publisher=[[ComputerWorld]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3245764/macs/the-t2-chip-makes-the-imac-pro-the-start-of-a-mac-revolution.html|title=The T2 chip makes the iMac Pro the start of a Mac revolution|publisher=[[Macworld]]}}</ref> T2 also delivers "enhanced imaging processing" for the iMac Pro's [[FaceTime|FaceTime HD]] camera.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://appleinsider.com/articles/17/12/12/imac-pro-debuts-custom-apple-t2-chip-to-handle-secure-boot-password-encryption-more/| title=iMac Pro debuts custom Apple T2 chip to handle secure boot, password encryption, more|website=[[AppleInsider]]|access-date=14 December 2017|date=12 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://appleinsider.com/articles/18/08/08/everything-you-need-to-know-about-apples-t2-chip-in-the-2018-macbook-pro|title=Everything you need to know about Apple's T2 chip in the 2018 MacBook Pro|website=[[AppleInsider]]|date=8 August 2018}}</ref> On July 12, 2018, Apple released an updated [[MacBook Pro]] that includes the T2 chip, which among other things enables the [[Siri#Features and options|"Hey Siri" feature]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rossignol |first1=Joe |title=Apple Launches 2018 MacBook Pros: 8th Gen Core, Up to 32GB of RAM, Third-Gen Keyboard, Quad-Core on 13-Inch and More |date=12 July 2018 |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2018/07/12/apple-launches-2018-macbook-pro-lineup/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |accessdate=12 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2018/07/apple-updates-macbook-pro-with-faster-performance-and-new-features-for-pros/|title=Apple updates MacBook Pro with faster performance and new features for pros|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]}}</ref> On November 7, 2018, Apple released an updated [[Mac mini]] and [[MacBook Air]] with the T2 chip.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Broussard |first1=Mitchel |title=Apple Announces New MacBook Air With 13-Inch Retina Display and Touch ID |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2018/10/30/apple-new-macbook-air/|website=[[MacRumors]] |date=30 October 2018 |accessdate=30 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hardwick |first1=Tim |title=Apple Announces New Space Gray Mac mini With 4-Core or 6-Core Intel Processor and Up to 64GB RAM, Starting at $799 |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2018/10/30/apple-announces-new-mac-mini/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=30 October 2018 |accessdate=30 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

== W series ==
The Apple "W" series is a family of [[system on a chip|"System on Chip" (SoC)]] and wireless chips with a focus on Bluetooth and Wi-Fi connectivity.

=== Apple W1 ===
The Apple W1 is a SoC from Apple used in the 2016 [[AirPods]] and select [[Beats Electronics|Beats headphones]].<ref name="forbes-w1">{{cite web |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/aarontilley/2016/09/07/apple-creates-its-first-wireless-chip-for-new-airpods/#19a1b3db7240 |title= Apple Creates Its First Wireless Chip For New Wireless Headphones, AirPods |first= Aaron |last= Tilley |work=[[Forbes]] }}</ref><ref name="macrumors-w1-beats">{{cite web |url= http://www.macrumors.com/2016/09/07/beats-by-dre-w1-chip/ |title= Apple Announces New Line of Beats Headphones With W1 Wireless Chip |work=[[MacRumors]] }}</ref> It maintains a [[Bluetooth]]<ref name="recode-w1">{{cite web |url= http://www.recode.net/2016/9/7/12841136/apple-airpods-do-use-bluetooth |title= Apple’s AirPods do use Bluetooth and they don’t require an iPhone 7 |work=[[Recode]] }}</ref> [[Bluetooth#Uses|Class 1]] connection with a computer device and decodes the audio stream that is sent to it.<ref name="Apple-airpods">{{cite web |url= https://www.apple.com/airpods/ |title= AirPods |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] }}</ref>

===Apple W2===
The Apple W2 is used in the [[Apple Watch Series 3]]. It is integrated into the [[Apple S3]] SiP. Apple released that the implementation of the chip makes Wi-Fi 85% faster and Bluetooth and Wi-Fi 50% more power efficient than the previous model's chip design.<ref name="apple-watch-series-3-pr"/>

===Apple W3===
The Apple W3 is used in the [[Apple Watch Series 4]]<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.apple.com/apple-watch-series-4/ |title= Apple Watch Series 4 |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |language= en-US |access-date= 2018-09-13 }}</ref> and [[Apple Watch Series 5|Series 5]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.apple.com/watch/compare/ |title= Apple Watch - Compare Models |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |language= en-US |access-date= 2018-09-13 }}</ref> It is integrated into the [[Apple S4]] and [[Apple S5]] SiPs. It supports Bluetooth 5.0.

== H series ==
=== Apple H1 ===
The Apple H1 chip was first used in the 2019 version of AirPods, and was later used in the Powerbeats Pro, the Beats Solo Pro, and the AirPods Pro.<ref>{{cite web |last= Mayo |first= Benjamin |title=New Apple AirPods now available: H1 chip, wireless charging case, hands-free Hey Siri |url= https://9to5mac.com/2019/03/20/new-apple-airpods-now-available-h1-chip-wireless-charging-case-hands-free-hey-siri/ |website=[[9to5Mac]] |accessdate= March 20, 2019 }}</ref> Specifically designed for headphones, it has Bluetooth 5.0, supports hands-free "Hey Siri" commands, and offers 30 percent lower latency compared to the W1 chip in the prior version of AirPods.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2019/03/airpods-the-worlds-most-popular-wireless-headphones-are-getting-even-better/ |title= AirPods, the world’s most popular wireless headphones, are getting even better |work=[[Apple Newsroom]] |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |language= en-US |access-date= 2019-03-21 }}</ref>

== U series ==
=== Apple U1 ===
The Apple U1 chip, introduced in the 2019 iPhones, uses [[Ultra Wideband]] technology for spatial awareness functions such as an improved, spatially-aware [[AirDrop]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sixcolors.com/post/2019/09/the-u1-chip-in-the-iphone-11-is-the-beginning-of-an-ultra-wideband-revolution/|title=The U1 chip in the iPhone 11 is the beginning of an Ultra Wideband revolution|author=Jason Snell|authorlink=Jason Snell|date=September 13, 2019|website=Six Colors}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/news/apple/149336-how-apple-s-u1-chip-adds-amazing-new-capabilities-to-the-iphone|title=How Apple's U1 chip adds 'amazing' new capabilities to the iPhone|author=Maggie Tillman|date=September 11, 2019|website=Pocket-lint}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/story/apple-u1-chip/|title=The Biggest iPhone News Is a Tiny New Chip Inside It|author=Brian Barrett|date=September 12, 2019|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]}}</ref>

